<DOC><DOCNO> AP891027-0003 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-89 0119EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-Robertson-PTL     10-27 0245</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Robertson-PTL,0252</SECOND><HEAD>CBN Submits Bid For PTL Network</HEAD><DATELINE>VIRGINIA BEACH, Va. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Christian Broadcasting Networkfounded by Marion G. ``Pat'' Robertson has submitted a bid to buythe PTL Network's cable operation, CBN spokeswoman FrankieAbourjilie said Thursday night.   ``All I can tell you is we have submitted a bid,'' Ms.Abourjilie said. ``There are numerous other bids.''   She said she could not comment on the amount of the bid becausethe bidding is confidential. ``If you divulge information relatedto the bid, they eliminate you,'' she said.   Ms. Abourjilie said she did not know when the bid was submitted,only that it was sent in time for Friday's deadline.   She said the PTL cable network reaches 7 million homes, comparedto 47 million reached by CBN. The bid is only for the cablenetwork, which includes satellites and cameras, Ms. Abourjiliesaid. The bid has ``nothing to do with Heritage USA,'' she said.   PTL filed for bankruptcy in June 1987, three months afterfounder Jim Bakker resigned as head of the the ministry amid a sexand money scandal.   Stephen Mernick, a Toronto businessman who had agreed to buy theministry's assets, let his purchase contract expire Sept. 30because he was unable to obtain title insurance for the HeritageUSA Christian campground near Fort Mill, S.C.   Jim Bakker on Tuesday began serving a 45-year prison sentencefor defrauding members of the defunct PTL Club and televisionministry of $3.7 million.</TEXT></DOC>